Dave Griffith (dave@blackjoke.bsd.uchicago.edu) wrote:

( never mind the security of the channel, how about the
recipient? )


True. But keeping the message from random third parties
is only *one* reason to use a public key; the more important
one I think is the fact that you can keep the identity
of the sender much more private if there is no need to
coordinate a private key first.

